		\chapter{INTRODUCTION}
	
Access to clean, safe, and accessible public restrooms is a basic human necessity that plays a crucial role in maintaining public health, hygiene, and individual dignity. Despite its importance, access to public sanitation remains a challenge in many parts of the world—especially in densely populated and rapidly urbanizing countries like India. The need becomes even more critical when people are traveling, commuting, or navigating unfamiliar areas, where locating a usable restroom can be difficult, frustrating, or even impossible.\vspace{12pt}\newline
In recent years, cities in India have witnessed considerable progress in adopting smart city initiatives—integrating technology to improve services in areas like transportation, energy, communication, and governance. However, one fundamental issue that continues to be neglected in these developments is the availability and management of public restrooms. While public toilets do exist, many suffer from poor maintenance, lack of accessibility, unclear location markers, or inadequate information for users.\vspace{12pt}\newline
The absence of a digital platform that provides real-time, reliable, and location-based information about public restroom facilities is a major gap in urban planning. Most people still rely on informal inquiries or random exploration to find nearby restrooms, which is inefficient and discourages proper hygiene practices.\vspace{12pt}\newline
it is a smart, user-centric, and location-aware public restroom detection system aimed at transforming how citizens locate and access public sanitation facilities. By leveraging mobile technology, geolocation, and user-generated data, LooLocator provides accurate, real-time information about nearby restrooms. Features include distance, gender designation (male, female, unisex), payment status (free or paid), accessibility for differently-abled individuals, and cleanliness ratings.\vspace{12pt}\newline
LooLocator addresses a recurring urban problem with a practical, scalable solution. It not only simplifies a daily need but also contributes to broader public health goals, promotes inclusive infrastructure, and supports the vision of cleaner, smarter cities in India.


