\chapter{\centering \bf \hspace*{}LITERATURE SURVEY}
\section{Literature Survey for Looloactor App }
Access to clean and accessible public restrooms remains a major challenge in densely populated urban areas, particularly in India. Despite sanitation initiatives like the Swachh Bharat Abhiyan, issues such as poor hygiene, lack of real-time visibility, and inadequate digital infrastructure continue to affect user satisfaction. Traditional methods like static signage or basic locator apps often fail to provide timely or accurate information about restroom availability, cleanliness, or accessibility. Applications such as Toilet Finder, SitOrSquat, and Flush offer GPS-based locating features but are limited by outdated data, low regional penetration, and minimal functionality beyond simple mapping.\vspace{12pt}\newline

The integration of Internet of Things (IoT) technologies has shown significant promise in addressing these issues. Sensors can monitor parameters such as occupancy, odor, humidity, and air quality, which helps in improving maintenance outcomes. Studies by Jain and Aggarwal (2021) demonstrate that microcontroller-based setups using Arduino or Raspberry Pi can provide enhanced operational insight and better hygiene management. While countries like Singapore and South Korea have begun implementing such technologies, they are mostly in pilot stages and lack seamless integration with mobile applications.\vspace{12pt}\newline

Digital payment systems and QR code authentication, widely adopted in retail and transportation in countries like China and Japan (Zhou, 2019), could also be applied to restroom access. Coupled with IoT-enabled smart locks, these systems can provide controlled access and facilitate efficient fee collection. However, such solutions remain largely unexplored in the public sanitation sector in India. These technologies have the potential to improve convenience, security, and operational efficiency when combined in an integrated system.\vspace{12pt}\newline

User-driven feedback mechanisms are another key factor in maintaining hygiene standards. Research by Ahmed and Kumar (2020) indicates that linking real-time user feedback to automated cleaning schedules can improve hygiene by 25–30 percent. Yet, these systems are often isolated and not connected to IoT frameworks or locator applications. Administrative dashboards exist for monitoring usage, triggering maintenance alerts, and managing access in select facilities such as hospitals and metro stations, but they are rarely integrated with mobile apps for end-users.\vspace{12pt}\newline

The primary research gap lies in creating a unified platform that combines GPS-based search, IoT monitoring, QR-based access, feedback collection, and administrative dashboards into a scalable solution. The LooLocator project addresses this gap by providing a mobile application that enables users to locate, access, and rate restrooms in real time while allowing administrators to monitor and maintain facilities remotely. This integrated approach not only enhances user convenience and hygiene but also supports smart city initiatives and sustainable urban sanitation management.\\
