\chapter{\centering \bf \hspace*{}SYSTEM ANALYSIS}
	
		\section{Existing system}
		

In the current scenario, access to public restrooms is managed through conventional and fragmented systems with minimal technological integration. Most cities rely on static infrastructure such as physical signboards, printed maps, or word-of-mouth directions to guide users to nearby toilets. These approaches are unreliable, especially for travelers, tourists, or individuals in unfamiliar areas. Many existing digital restroom locator applications like Toilet Finder, Flush, and SitOrSquat offer basic GPS-based location services but lack features like real-time availability, cleanliness ratings, or maintenance updates. Consequently, users often encounter restrooms that are either closed, poorly maintained, or unhygienic.\vspace{12pt}\newline

Municipal bodies and local authorities typically maintain public sanitation records manually or through isolated digital spreadsheets. These systems do not provide any form of real-time monitoring or feedback collection from users. As a result, it becomes difficult to track restroom usage patterns, detect maintenance issues promptly, or ensure consistent cleanliness standards. The absence of an integrated management system also leads to inefficiencies in resource allocation for cleaning and maintenance schedules.\vspace{12pt}\newline

From the user’s perspective, existing systems fail to deliver essential information such as restroom accessibility for differently-abled individuals, operating hours, or payment requirements. Moreover, there is no digital mechanism for users to report issues or provide feedback about hygiene conditions. This lack of communication between users and maintenance authorities results in recurring problems being left unresolved.\vspace{12pt}\newline

Some smart city initiatives have experimented with sensor-based restroom monitoring; however, these implementations are often limited to high-traffic areas like airports, metro stations, or malls. These isolated setups typically operate independently without public access through mobile platforms. Furthermore, they rarely incorporate modern technologies like IoT-based lock control, QR authentication, or digital payment systems that can streamline access and improve accountability.\vspace{12pt}\newline

Overall, the existing restroom management ecosystem remains highly fragmented, inefficient, and user-unfriendly. There is a pressing need for a comprehensive, data-driven, and user-interactive solution that integrates GPS navigation, IoT-based monitoring, and digital services into a single accessible platform. The LooLocator system aims to overcome these shortcomings by introducing an intelligent, real-time restroom management and accessibility platform designed for urban environments.\vspace{12pt}
