\section{Feasibility Study}
A feasibility study is essential for assessing the practicality and potential success of the proposed system. It evaluates different aspects to determine whether the LooLocator project is achievable within constraints such as time, technology, and cost. The following are the primary areas of feasibility analysis:

\subsection{ Operational Feasibility}
The proposed system is designed with the end-user in mind, offering intuitive navigation, location-based restroom search, and secure digital access. Since the application is aimed at a wide demographic—including commuters, tourists, and people in unfamiliar urban areas—its operational model emphasizes user-friendliness and reliability. The admin module ensures efficient monitoring and upkeep of restroom facilities. Overall, the system is highly operationally feasible and aligns well with existing smart city initiatives like Swachh Bharat.

\subsection{Technical Feasibility}

The LooLocator application utilizes widely available and mature technologies such as GPS for geolocation, mobile applications for user interaction, cloud storage for real-time data access, QR scanning for secure entry, and IoT-based modules for smart restroom door unlocking. These components are technically sound, scalable, and compatible with current infrastructure across Android, iOS, and web platforms. Integration with third-party APIs like Google Maps, UPI-based payment gateways (e.g., Paytm, PhonePe, Razorpay), and Firebase or MySQL databases is straightforward, thanks to comprehensive developer documentation and community support.

From a hardware perspective, the use of cost-effective microcontrollers such as Arduino or Raspberry Pi for the IoT modules ensures that the system remains technically feasible in both urban and semi-urban implementations. The smart locking mechanism can be controlled remotely and integrated easily into the cloud platform, providing robust performance with low latency.

From the end-user perspective, the system is technically feasible due to its reliance on familiar and accessible technologies. Most users already possess smartphones with internet connectivity, GPS capability, and a built-in camera for QR scanning. The app interface is designed to be lightweight, user-friendly, and responsive across devices, ensuring smooth operation even in areas with moderate internet bandwidth. Users are not required to learn new hardware or complex interfaces—the interaction with the system is intuitive and minimal.

Therefore, considering both administrative and user standpoints, the LooLocator system is technically feasible, deployable with existing technologies, and offers the potential for future enhancements without requiring substantial infrastructure changes.

\subsection{ Economical Feasibility}
The project involves initial setup costs for IoT hardware, software development, server hosting, and maintenance. However, once deployed, the operational costs are relatively low due to automation and remote monitoring. Revenue can be generated via paid restroom access or government/public sector funding under smart infrastructure schemes. Considering the long-term public health benefits, reduced manual labor, and minimal running costs, the project is economically viable.

  
