\section{Actors And Roles}
The LooLocator system involves multiple actors, each with distinct responsibilities to ensure the efficient functioning of the platform. These actors include end users, administrators, and IoT devices, all working together within a connected ecosystem.

\subsection*{3.6.1 End Users}
End users are the primary actors who interact with the system. Their responsibilities include:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Using the mobile or web application to search for nearby restrooms via GPS.
  \item Applying filters based on:
  \begin{itemize}
    \item Gender designation,
    \item Cleanliness,
    \item Accessibility,
  \end{itemize}
  \item Scanning QR codes for restroom access.
  \item Making digital payments if required.
  \item Submitting cleanliness ratings.
  \item Reporting maintenance or hygiene issues.
  \item Contributing real-time feedback to maintain accurate restroom data and improve hygiene standards.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{3.6.2 Admin}
Admins (system administrators) manage backend operations and ensure overall system functionality:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Approving and updating restroom listings.
  \item Monitoring usage logs.
  \item Remotely unlocking or locking restroom doors in emergencies.
  \item Responding to user complaints and reports.
  \item Ensuring IoT device functionality and maintenance.
  \item Overseeing hygiene compliance and quality standards.
  \item Analyzing dashboard data to enhance services.
  \item Acting as the communication link between users and the physical restroom infrastructure.
\end{itemize}


\chapter{SYSTEM DESIGN}

\section{Methodology}
The development of the LooLocator system was based on the Agile software engineering paradigm, specifically the SCRUM methodology, to promote iterative progress, stakeholder collaboration, and adaptability throughout the project lifecycle. Clearly defined SCRUM roles ensured smooth execution, with the product owner managing the backlog, the development team implementing core features like GPS mapping, QR-based access, digital payments, and IoT integration, and the scrum master facilitating workflow and resolving impediments. The system followed a structured development approach beginning with requirement analysis and UML-based system design, progressing through modular development of components such as location tracking, restroom display, payment interface, IoT door control, and admin dashboard. Modern technologies like Flutter or React Native for mobile, Node.js or Python for backend, MySQL or Firebase for databases, and Arduino or Raspberry Pi for IoT integration were employed, alongside APIs like Google Maps and Razorpay to enhance functionality. After modular testing and integration, the system was deployed on cloud infrastructure for scalability and high availability. In operation, users locate restrooms, make digital payments, and unlock doors via IoT-enabled QR codes, while administrators monitor usage and analytics in real time through a web dashboard. This agile, modular, and technology-driven approach ensured that LooLocator met its objectives effectively while remaining adaptable for future smart sanitation innovations.
